reflection on the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have tabled a legislative proposal to establish the organisation of trade unions as civil rights .
&quot; as trade unions die , middle class jobs die , &quot; said Ellison , a Minnesota democrat , and vice president of the Progressive Caucus in Congress .
that is why I am proud to present the employee authorisation law together with John Lewis , the civil rights officer .
this groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal opportunities for discrimination on the grounds of the organisation of trade unions as in other forms of discrimination - and stops anti @-@ union forces .
the addition of the national labour law to create a way of discriminating workers to organise a trade union representation in order to bring justice before a civil court - and to obtain damages or penalties - is a useful and necessary initiative .
but it is certainly not a radical initiative - certainly not American standards .
indeed , the best way to understand what Ellison , Lewis and the other sponsors of her bill propose is to link back to a very American idea .
despite the setbacks experienced by trade unions in recent years - in Wisconsin , Michigan , and other states across the country - Americans once encouraged countries around the world to recognize , expand , and respect labor rights .
there was a time when millions of Americans remember when this country called democracy , freedom of speech , freedom of the press and the right of association in one breath .
when the United States occupied Japan after World War II , General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to adopt a constitution to ensure that militarized autocracy Hedki Tojos would be replaced by democracy .
fully aware that workers and their unions have a role to play in creating a new Japan , they used a language that explicitly recognised that &quot; workers &quot; rights to unification and collective negotiation and action are guaranteed . &quot;
when the United States occupied Germany after World War II , General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler &apos;s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy .
in recognition of the fact that workers would have to organise themselves and raise their voices in the new nation , the Germans added a clause explicitly stating : &quot; the right to set up associations to safeguard and improve working and economic conditions is guaranteed to each individual and every profession or profession .
agreements that restrict or seek to reduce this right are null and void ; measures aimed at doing so are illegal .
when former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Human Rights Commission , which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights , as assumed by the United Nations as a global agreement in 1948 , Roosevelt and the other authors added a guarantee that &quot; everyone has the right to form unions to protect their interests . &quot;
for generations , Americans have accepted the basic premise that labour rights are human rights .
when that country told other countries how to form civil and democratic societies , Americans said that the right to establish a trade union - and that this union should then be allowed to participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government agencies - must be protected .
indeed , after these rights were attacked in America , it is very wise to look back at the American ideal , whereby working people must have the right to unite and make themselves heard in a free and open society .
as Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago :
history is a great teacher .
now everyone knows that the workers &quot; movement did not limit the nation &apos;s strength , but increased it .
by raising the standard of living of millions of people , work has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production .
those who attack work forget these simple truths , but history keeps them .
history reminds us , and we should .
the formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of employee representatives - is long overdue .
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are renewing the ideals that made America great in the past , fulfilling the promise of democracy .
judge temporarily stops all abortion clinics in Louisiana forcing them to close down
on Sunday , a US federal judge provisionally stopped the implementation of a law in Louisiana , which lawyers say would probably have led to the closure of all five abortion clinics in the state .
this measure , imposed by Bobby Jindal , Governor of Louisiana , in June and intended to enter into force on 1 September , would force doctors carrying out abortions to acquire a patient &apos;s right of admission at a hospital within a radius of 30 miles to practice .
however , the judge &apos;s decision means that doctors can temporarily continue to carry out legal abortions while applying for such a right .
&quot; the plaintiff can continue to work in accordance with the law while seeking to obtain these rights , &quot; Federal Judge John deGravelles wrote in his judgment .
a hearing for the judge will be held within one month to bring about a more permanent decision for the law .
those in favour of abortion welcomed the decision , the latest in a series of judgments against similar measures , saying that doctors would have more time to obtain hospital ID rights .
&quot; today &apos;s decision means that women in Louisiana are escaping a careless law that wants to deprive them of their health and rights , &quot; said Nancy Northup , President and Chair of the Reproductive Rights Centre , which had indicted them on behalf of three of the five clinics of the state to stop the law .
it was not immediately clear whether the judgment also covered doctors from the two clinics who had not joined the complaint and had also applied for admission rights .
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have enacted similar laws , with courts recently declared such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi .
key points of a law in Texas that would have forced most of the clinics remaining in the state to close down were stopped by a federal judge on Friday .
abortion advocates and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists , as well as the American Medical Association , are unanimous in saying that doctors &quot; rights of admission require unnecessary restrictions .
those opposed to abortion preclude the fact that the measures are designed to protect women &apos;s health , although some also welcomed the effects of closure of clinics .
only a doctor who carries out abortions in Louisiana has access to patients &apos; rights , informed the Reproduction Rights Centre .
if all other doctors in the state are forced to stop abortions , that doctor would no longer perform the operation for fear of safety , the group said .
in their arguments against the judgment , representatives of the State of Louisiana said that they would not punish doctors for carrying out abortions while their applications for patients &apos; rights would still be pending .
delayed diagnosis and lack of access to the best treatments result in higher death rates due to egg stock cancer in rural areas .
Angelina Jolie and her brother James have made a video debut for their mother who died in 2007 from ovarian cancer .
women in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying of ovarian cancer than women in cities .
researchers analysed the medical data of more than 1100 Australians diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005 , and found that only 25 % were alive five years after diagnosis .
the research director Susan Jordan of QIMR Berghofer Medical Research Institute said that for those living in rural and remote regions of the state , mortality was 20 % higher during the study than for those living in urban areas .
small STUFFS : new medicines could slow lung and ovarian cancer
researchers investigated the medical care of women over seven years .
Dr. Jordan said that the age of a woman in diagnosis , type of ovarian cancer , existing precursors and social and economic status also affected survival opportunities .
for older women and those whose cancer was already advanced at the diagnostic stage , the survival rate was lowest .
for those living in rural and remote regions of the state , the risk of mortality was 20 % higher during the study than in urban areas .
although the study did not examine why women living outside the city were more likely to die of ovarian cancer , Dr. Jordan suspect that a late diagnosis and a lack of access to the best treatment centres are possible factors .
&quot; this disease is best treated by gynaecological oncology , and these are usually found in larger cities , &quot; she said .
despite the improvement of telemedicine services in order to counter the distances , she proposed , as a possible remedy , a strengthening of the service of interfered doctors in order to give specialists the opportunity to care for women in their place of residence , as well as treatment programmes for people outside their region .
Dr Jordan said that , regardless of geographical status , the study revealed a poor long @-@ term survival rate for women in ovarian cancer and stressed the need for better treatment and prevention strategies .
the study funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer is published today in the Medical Journal of Australia .
in March 2013 , Elisha Neave , a young 33 @-@ year @-@ old mother from the Golden Coast , discovered that she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer .
garden centres regret falling house numbers
the decline , together with an increase in the number of homeowners under the age of 35 , could result in garden centres losing tens of thousands of pounds a year if today &apos;s young consumers reach the &quot; core age group for horticultural products , &quot; according to a study by HTA .
the report states that , on average , tenants spend 55 % of the amount that people spend on their garden with their homes .
the increase in people living in highly urbanised areas without gardens , the popular method of asphalting gardens for parking purposes and the declining garden size are other factors that threaten the industry , where an estimated £ 5 billion is sold annually .
in the London area , where the share of homeowners has fallen from 61 % to 43 % over a period of 6 years , the lowest expenditure on garden products per household is reported .
the HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society point out that housing for rent or small gardens does not mean that people cannot draw plants .
Guy Barter , Chief Garrison Advisor for the RHS , said : &quot; container gardeners are very popular with tenants , for example , because they can take their plants with them when they move . &quot;
the HTA report identified the period between 1997 and 2005 as the &quot; golden age &quot; of garden retailing due to rising house ownership and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid @-@ 1990s .
he also predicted an improved market situation this year due to better weather conditions in March and April last year .
