house prices have experienced the highest winter rise in seven years , showing a widely observed index .
the RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic Home Value Index for homes in the Australian capital increased by 1.1 percent in August , according to Monday &apos;s RP data .
as a result of this increase , the overall increase in June , July and August is 4.2 % , the largest increase in winter months since 2007 .
the annual price increase was 10.9 % , more than twice the increase in the 12 months to August 2013 , but increases were not evenly spread across the country .
RP Data &apos;s research director , Tim Lawless , announced that Sydney and Melbourne are driving a two @-@ tier market .
RP Data &apos;s figures show that house prices in Sydney increased by 16.1 % last year , while in Melbourne they rose by 11.7 % .
the following markets are Adelaide , Brisbane and Darwin , where prices rose by five and six percent on average .
at the other end of the scale is Canberra , which was hit hard by cuts in government spending , where prices rose by just 1.4 % over the year .
Mr Lawless went on to say that , with the beginning of spring , there would be an increase in the number of real estate on sale over the next few months , which would &apos; test &apos; the market .
&quot; if you look at the consistently high rate of auction prices , a generally fast sales rate , and the consistently low rate of interest , it is likely that home prices will rise even further in the next three months , &quot; he said .
