Kenya registers officials to contain ghost workers
Kenya has begun to register all state officials biometric to remove &quot; ghosts &quot; from government pay lists .
employees who do not register in the next two weeks would no longer be paid , was a government communication .
the government estimates that thousands of people will still receive pay after leaving the public service .
President Uhuru Kenyatta promised to fight corruption in the civil service when he took office in 2013 .
at the beginning of this year &apos;s audit , it was found that at least $ 1 million ( £ 700,000 ) per month were lost in payments for &quot; ghost workers &quot; and other abusive financial practices .
the government estimates that salaries will continue to be paid to accounts after a person has died or leaves the public service , says Wanyama Chebusiri for the BBC from the capital Nairobi .
all officials will now have to appear at identification centres in the next two weeks to ensure that their data on biometric registrations are recorded , a government message was sent .
those who would not do so without a credible apology would be removed from the payroll , the communication continued .
&quot; this approach will make a significant contribution to the rationalisation of the public service by identifying the actual number of civil servants and also by redressing the payroll at both levels of government - eliminating the &quot; ghosts , &quot; said Anne Waiguru , Cabinet Secretary at the Ministry of Decentralisation and Planning .
