Berkeley declares housing market &quot; normal &quot; again
one of London &apos;s most prominent builders pointed out that the housing market in the south @-@ east of England has returned to normal levels .
home homes in the capital were hotly sought @-@ after and the subject of huge price increases , prompting the Bank of England to set caps on mortgage loans in June , owing to widespread fear of a credit bubble .
Tony Pidgley , founder and CEO of the high @-@ class construction company Berkeley said on Monday : &quot; since the beginning of the current financial year , the market has returned to normal transaction levels since the peak of 2013 , &quot; adding that this offers a &quot; stable handling environment . &quot;
the housing market in London was well positioned during the downturn , as foreign buyers pushed into the capital .
according to the register office , prices in the urban area rose sharply last year alone by 18.5 % , far more than the average increase in England and Wales as a whole .
Berkeleys &quot; average selling prices for private , inexpensive , and student offers rose by about one @-@ fifth last year and reached £ 423,000 at the end of April .
but a stronger pound has made real estate in London less attractive to foreign buyers in recent months - some of them have been deterred by the introduction of new property taxes and political rhetoric for a possible &quot; housing tax &quot; before the general elections next May .
the London real estate broker Foxton warned last week that the April mortgage market report , which presented tighter credit procurement rules , would lead to lower market growth in both real estate sales and prices in the second half of the year .
new data from the Bank of England on Monday show a decline in mortgage approval in July , which also suggests that the housing market is cooling .
Hamptions International , another real estate agency , corrected its forecast for the rise in housing prices in London for 2015 to 3 % , on the basis of an already weakening house price awareness .
the volume of transactions in the most expensive areas of London such as Chelsea , Mayfair and Kensington has now fallen by a quarter year after year , according to Makler WA Ellis .
nevertheless , the desire to have a home in the capital for Berkeley is a blessing , as the due amounts for futures sales amount to more than £ 2.2 billion .
Mr Pidgley added : &quot; the demand for the right , well @-@ planned product at the best locations remained stable and the result was stable sales . &quot;
in June , the company reported that it had sold 3,742 new homes in the year until the end of April - almost a third more than the pre @-@ crisis peak in 2007 .
the annual pre @-@ tax result rose by 40 percent to £ 280 million annually , while sales rose by 18 percent to £ 1.6 billion .
in a communication on Monday before the company &apos;s annual meeting , Mr Pidgley said that the revenue for Berkeley is expected to be in line with current market expectations this year .
analysts agree that the annual pre @-@ tax result is £ 450 million .
Berkeley shares were fixed in London in the afternoon at £ 23.96 .
