Lesotho military member says no coup is planned ; Prime Minister remains in South Africa
officials in Lesotho denied planning a coup d &apos;état to overthrow the government and said that they were going against policemen accused of arming political fanatics .
Prime Minister Thomas Thabane fled the country and announced that the country &apos;s army had converted its seat of office and occupied government buildings in the capital Maseru .
the Prime Minister brought his family to neighbouring South Africa after reporting threats of aggression .
military spokesman Major Ntlele Ntoi said that there is no de facto coup , but that the military is responding to the threat posed by &quot; political fanatics , &quot; whose arming was imminent by the police .
&quot; what happened this morning was that the staff of Lesotho &apos;s defense forces acted after receiving several intelligence reports that some elements within the police actually wanted to arm some of the political , party @-@ political young fanatics who were about to cause devastating damage , &quot; he said to Voice of America .
South African government spokesman Clayson Monyela said that the military action had made the impression of a surge .
&quot; although no one has claimed to have torn the government through violence , all reports agree that Lesotho &apos;s defence forces have so far shown signs of a coup d &apos;état , &quot; he said .
spokesmen of the Lesotho military told us on Sunday that the soldiers were going back to their barracks and that the situation in the capital was calm .
meanwhile , Deputy Prime Minister Mothetjoya Metsing takes over governance while Thabanes is absent .
Thabane announced that he believed he had been targeted because of his attempt to fight corruption in the country .
