he said that his actions had not undermined the government , despite different accusations .
euro area output at a 13 @-@ month low
the rise in output in the eurozone slowed to the lowest point of the last 13 months in August , according to a carefully observed study .
the final Markit purchasing management index of the manufacturing industry ( PMI ) fell to 50.7 in August , after 51.8 in July .
an increase of 50 indicates an expansion .
new orders fell and factories experienced collapses in a time of rising tensions between the EU and Russia over Ukraine .
the figures arrive before the European Central Bank ( ECB ) meeting on Thursday .
markets expect the Bank to adopt a clear plan for dealing with a slow recovery in the eurozone and for the threat of deflation at just 0.3 % inflation .
there is speculation that the head of the ECB , Mario Draghi , could provide further information later this week as to whether he is considering quantitative easing for the eurozone , according to those made by Britain and the US during the financial crisis .
&quot; although small growth is better than no growth , the dampening effects of rising economic and geopolitical uncertainties have become clearer for manufacturers , &quot; said Rob Dobson , leading economist at Markit .
the factory PMI for Germany , Russia &apos;s largest trading partner in the EU , fell to the lowest level in 11 months with 51.4 .
meanwhile , in the second largest economy of the block , France , PMI fell to 46.9 .
France remains a sorcerer and Italy &apos;s departure from solid expansion to stagnation .
hints that growth incentives in key industries in Germany and in Spain and the Netherlands are no longer effective are not reassuring either , &quot; said Mr Dobson .
the decline in industry is likely to fuel analysts &quot; fire , who expect further monetary or fiscal incentives .
positive news came from the Republic of Ireland , where PMI rose to 57.3 , the highest level since the end of 1999 .
Howard Archer , Chief Economic Expert at IHS Global Insight , said : &quot; the best that one can say for the purchasing management index of the manufacturing industry in the euro area in August is that the sector continues to grow . &quot;
he added : &quot; eurozone producers seem to find life rather difficult at the moment , as the current heightened geopolitical tensions - particularly with regard to Russia and Ukraine - are increasing uncertainties in the still difficult conditions in many countries .
these increased uncertainties have clearly affected the economy - especially , and consumer confidence - and are likely to cause some orders to be delayed or even cancelled , especially large orders .
he said that it would &quot; become more and more likely &quot; that the ECB would eventually have to launch a kind of QE , &quot; though we suspect that this will be limited . &quot;
