4 tips for better underwater photos and videos
if you would like to take photos or videos under water , there is a selection of devices .
the cheapest option is a waterproof point @-@ and @-@ shoot , such as the Nikon Coolpix AW120 or an action cam like the GoPro Hero3 + Silver Edition , both for about $ 300 .
I have taken these photos with a family party with several cameras , all available at a price of less than $ 350 .
regardless of the equipment , there are some rules for the best results .
check your equipment twice .
even if you have a waterproof camera , make sure that the battery compartment and other subjects are sealed .
add your camera to the photos or videos you want to take .
some cameras and camcorder have scene and recording modes that optimize exposure time for the humid underwater conditions .
and before you jump into it , check the depth of your equipment .
some cameras are only allowed for up to 5 feet , others up to 50 or 60 feet .
search for digital cameras for conventional and waterproof models in our purchasing guide .
take multiple shots - because many will not fold .
point @-@ and @-@ Shoot cameras have an LCD to compose images , Action @-@ Cams usually do not .
even if you have an LCD , it is difficult to see this under water , and the right image setting is a matter of luck .
so take many pictures .
if your camera has a series mode that takes a series of pictures with slightly changed exposure settings , use it .
stay close to the surface .
the light becomes dramatically worse , the further you move from the surface .
if possible , you will stay close to the surface if you take pictures in a pool , lake or sea .
this allows you to add more color to your photos ; the deeper you go , the less color you will see .
go close to the objects .
this is also a good advice on land , but it is all the more important under water because of poor light conditions .
it is particularly important to work with an action cam : these devices often have a fixed wide angle lens , which means that you have to get closer to your objects if they are to complete the entire image frame .
Andrew Lawson was a man of the variety whose character changed things , even in a gigantic organization like the NHS .
as an expert anaesthesia , he devoted his career to saving patients from both the disease &apos;s agony and the pain of treatment .
among his patients , his wife recalls , was a MI6 employee who had to live with the devastating effects of torture .
Lawson knew that doctors are important for diagnoses and diseases , while the treated are mostly concerned with something quite different : pain .
one day in 2007 , however , he was the one whose path of suffering began .
he wrote in May of this year .
I had difficulty getting up .
as he struggled with flu @-@ like symptoms , he noticed that he impatiently accused his wife Juliet .
&quot; I prefer everything immediately than later , &quot; he said .
when Juliet was on a business trip for a week , Lawson felt quite unusual and uneasy .
something was in the air .
he asked a colleague to carry out an X @-@ ray examination of his breast .
only two weeks ago he was skiing in the French Alps .
the results of the X @-@ ray investigation were available .
he suffered from Mesotheliom , an incurable cancer that attacks the breast skin , that is to say the lungs .
as with most cancers , the exact trigger is usually difficult to determine .
for example , while some smokers suffer from lung cancer , not all lung cancer patients were previously smokers .
but Mesotheliom is different .
in almost all cases , the trigger is an asbestos load - contact with the fibre building material , which was once considered a &quot; miracle material , &quot; but has now been recognized as deadly .
for most of us , Mesotheliom is a disease that can easily be ignored .
asbestos is a product of the past .
the most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in Britain since the 1960 &quot; s , when industry voluntarily undertook to stop using it .
even where it was still used , only people in certain industries worked directly with the fabric - plumbers , construction workers , carpentry workers and shipyard workers , for example .
as an industrial hazardous material from another time , it seems to be hardly worrying today .
but this complacency is inappropriate .
Britain , it seems , is now experiencing the climax of a Mesoltheliom epidemic .
there are more deaths from Mesotheliom here than in any other country in the world .
with a total of 2,500 deaths per year , twice as many people die from this disease as in road accidents .
annual figures for measuring cancer cases since 1980 and likely future deaths in the UK
the reason why we are now experiencing the deadly effects , even though asbestos has been illegal for years ( in 1999 all types of asbestos were banned ) is that a mesothelioma only develops after decades .
and the scourge of the Mesotheliom is not confined to former construction workers .
asbestos was , and is often still present in the houses in which we live , the offices in which we work , the schools in which we learn and the shops in which we buy .
so Mesotheliom knows no class barriers , financial limits , professions , or age .
the privileged bastions , from the elegant department stores in London to private schools , are not a protected area .
Parliament &apos;s buildings are contaminated by asbestos .
even in hospitals where we are supposed to be healthy , this deadly carcinogens has already been identified as the starting point .
Andrew Lawson was not old .
he was not a plumber either .
he did indeed find it hard to imagine where he might have come into contact with asbestos .
then he found it out .
&quot; it looks like there was a lot of asbestos in the tunnels at Guy &apos;s Hospital , where I spent six years training . &quot; he wrote .
all - students , nurses , doctors and nurses - use the tunnels .
one wonders how many of my colleagues will suffer from the same disease ?
unfortunately , he was able to answer this question in part at least .
&quot; of the four doctors trained at Guy &apos;s Hospital and who have been sick of Mesotheliom in the last five years , &quot; he wrote in a letter in 2010 , &quot; I am the last to live . &quot;
how many of us will suffer ?
Andrew Lawson was diagnosed at the age of 48 .
when he died on 17 February this year , he was 55 .
this was an unusually long survival period .
fifty per cent of all Mesothelian patients die within 8 months of diagnosis .
the disease is always fatal .
so we can only repeat Lawson &apos;s question : &quot; how many of us will be sick ? &quot;
the UK &apos;s leading expert on Mesotheliom , Professor Julian Peto , assumes that , between 1870 and 2050 , when the asbestos vaccination in the UK is expected to come to an end , a total of 90,000 of the disease will have been lost .
most of them currently have no idea that they will die .
an asbestos mine in Quebec , Canada Alamy
a brief look at the files of the courts , which the parties concerned often turn to for damages claims , shows how widespread the scourge of the Mesothelian is .
in June this year , Marks &amp; Spencer , for example , admitted that Janice Allen had accidentally suspended asbestos .
she worked for nine years for the chain , from 1978 to 1987 , and was responsible for the clothing department at two locations - one of which was the flagship store at Oxford Street .
Mrs. Allen was only 18 years old when she started her business at M &amp; S .
now she has two children in the twenties .
&quot; before this thing , &quot; she says , &quot; I had never heard of Mesotheliom before , I didn &apos;t even know anything about asbestos .
I would never have thought that would affect me .
there are few people who know a lot about asbestos .
the fact is that the term asbestos refers not to a substance , but to a group of six minerals .
the name derives from the word &quot; asemic form , &quot; a description of the fibre structure that makes the fabric resistant and flexible .
three of the six were used in construction .
Chrysotil , also known as white asbestos , is by far the most commonly found asbestos in buildings .
it was used for roofs , floor panels , pipe isolations , pit insulation , even for brake coverings in cars .
it is less deadly than other forms of asbestos , but it is still regarded by the EU and the WHO as a &quot; major health risk &quot; with possible death .
however , the brown asbestos ( Amosit ) and blue asbestos ( Krokydolith ) are more dangerous .
Britain was once the world &apos;s largest importer of brown asbestos , and experts suspect that &quot; there is clear , but indirect , evidence that this was a major reason for the uniquely high rate of measurement . &quot;
a Marks &amp; Spencer employee was exposed to Alamy at the flagship store in Oxford Street , London .
Janice Allen may not have seen himself as a typical witness , but Julian Peto &apos;s work suggests that her story is by no means unusual .
he has presented a study of those affected , which shows that &quot; a significant proportion of the measuring elioma was caused by work or probably by asbestos contact in the environment without a known suspension . &quot;
most of these contacts are based on the &quot; normal use and ageing &quot; of our buildings .
it seems that no one can assume that they are safe .
a report by Goddard Consulting , which examined the palace of Westminster , shows how people could have been unwittingly exposed to the substance in the heart of the government .
in 2009 , Goddard reported that service stores and pipelines were contaminated with asbestos behind Parliament &apos;s committee rooms , whose deadly fibres could be blown up by something as harmless as &quot; strong air movements . &quot;
members of parliament are often accused of taking care of their own interests , but here it seems that the opposite is true .
while the Directorate of the Parliamentary Labour Service insisted that the Westminster Palace had received a &quot; clean health certificate , &quot; it is now undeniable that £ 1 billion of work has to be spent over several years in order to renovate Parliament , modernize the electrical installations and remove asbestos , and that after the general elections in 2015 , MEPs will be more likely to meet .
the Goddard report also pointed out that &quot; the presence of asbestos was not handled in accordance with the relevant provisions . &quot;
no one can know whether this mismanagement will cost lives .
all we can do now is wait .
a person who has never been able to determine the contact with Asbestos is Graham Abbott , a general practitioner .
like Andrew Lawson , 50 @-@ year @-@ old Abbott suspect that he was exposed to asbestos during his work in hospitals .
&quot; I worked in a hospital where asbestos actions were taken positively , &quot; he says , &quot; but I cannot prove it in my case .
it is so difficult to remember all the places you have worked on and the data .
what he reminds us of is the day at the beginning of December 2009 when he got a kind of fever .
he was 45 , and just late in the evening carried out an operation .
suddenly I had Schüttelfrost .
suddenly .
I felt terrible .
I thought I could not make the trip home any more .
as a doctor Abbott knew that the pain was caused by the breast skin , the skin around his lungs .
but like Janice Allen , he had no reason to suspect a Mesotheliom .
he did not go to work for a month .
amazed doctors took X @-@ ray shots of his chest and started Pleurakathether to extract liquid from the lungs and test it in the laboratory .
his complaints , however , remained undiagnosed .
his health slowly improved and he returned to his job .
from time to time , however , the symptoms returned , often after sporting activity and intense breathing .
in 2011 , a patient came out with similar symptoms in his practice and was later diagnosed with Mesotheliom .
but again Abbott did not associate this with his own case .
after all , his patient was several decades older and had worked directly with asbestos .
the connection in the case was clear .
in September 2011 , Abbott &apos;s condition deteriorated and his physician brought his CT scans and X @-@ rays to an expert group .
in December 2011 , exactly two years after Abbott felt sick for the first time , a probe equipped with a camera was introduced into the cave between the rip and breast skin .
I am an optimist .
I usually just go on , &quot; he says .
frankly , I did not worry so much .
but Rachel , my wife , was worried .
the result of the biopsy was between Christmas and New Year : &quot; I was told that it was Mesotheliom . &quot;
Graham Abbott : diagnostic Mesotheliom
suddenly Abbott had appointments with Macmillan nurses , one of whom recommended him to take a lawyer .
only now did he see the scale of the epidemic .
&quot; it turned out that asbestos was very widespread , especially in large public buildings where pipes were often isolated from asbestos , &quot; he says .
the people exposed to asbestos in these buildings are now sick .
and so Mesotheliom now meets younger people who have not worked in the typical professions .
the most dangerous pipes with asemic insulation in hospitals were under the earth , so patients were probably not exposed to the substance .
but many people who moved from one building to another in pedestrian tunnels ( like Andrew Lawson ) or in underground canteens ( as Graham Abbott often did ) were most likely in contact with toxic substances .
it turns out that over several decades after the war , hospitals may have been life @-@ saving for patients , but they are life @-@ threatening for the physicians .
it is still being removed today .
students turned their bunch burners on asbestos mats .
and it is not just about hospitals .
asbestos was often used in offices , shops , libraries and city halls because of its fabulous isolation and flame retardant properties .
schools .
indeed , many people probably had the first asbestos contact in the classroom .
throughout the country , in thousands of chemical dogs , students have switched their bunker burners to asbestos mats .
the issue of asbestos in schools is frequently raised on websites .
and meanwhile , innocent items in our houses , such as floor panels or drawers , have by default included asbestos .
&quot; it is an industrial gift that is included in much of our real estate , &quot; says Andrew Morgan , the lawyer who represented Andrew Lawson in his trial of Guy &apos;s Hospital .
in one case , the only contact that struck an affected woman was the demolition of a garden shoe in the 1970s .
so take care of how to tear off your garden shoes .
the effects of diagnosis , and the knowledge that the disease is incurable , is immense .
&quot; it takes a while to process it , &quot; says Graham Abbott .
I went back to work and tried to continue , but I noticed that I could not concentrate on what I did .
I was in practice for two weeks .
then I knew that I had to go and take care of myself .
well , I will not see another Christmas party .
with the greatest difficulty was the change of perspective from the position of a doctor to that of a patient .
like countless patients before him , he remembers how overwhelmed he was by all the information he had to deal with .
&quot; it was very difficult to include everything , &quot; he says .
&quot; I asked my doctor &quot; how long did I have ? &quot;
and I was given about 12 months .
I remember that I thought , &quot; well , I will not see another Christmas .
that was then . &quot;
Mesotheliom is particularly insidious because it is our life @-@ keeping mechanism - breathing itself - that causes deadly cancer .
most cases of Mesotheliom are caused by asbestos contact .
asbestos consists of smallest fibres .
when asbestos is blown up and the fibres are inhaled , they can be fixed in the breast skin , the skin around the lungs .
asbestos fibres irritate the breast skin and can cause cell mutations .
&quot; the problem arises with infiltrated needle @-@ shaped asbestos fibres , &quot; says Professor Tom Treasure , a cardiovascular doctor who moved to Guy &apos;s Hospital in 2001 .
it is precisely the hospital that Andrew Lawson suspect has exposed him to asbestos that is now ironically a leading centre in the treatment of Mesotheliom .
Treasure knew Lawson and treated some others who were probably also exposed to asbestos during their training in hospital .
as soon as the asbestos needles reach the lung tissue , Treasure says , &quot; they are pushed from breathing to the edge where the skin is .
from the very beginning it is invasive .
the usual options for other cancers do not work well with Mesotheliom .
for example , the effectiveness of an operation is highly controversial .
some say it is worth trying .
Treasure denies this .
&quot; you cannot cut the breast skin out , &quot; he says .
they don &apos;t come around with the knife .
in the meantime , cancer &quot; does not speak very well about chemotherapy , &quot; which shows &quot; effect , &quot; but does not cure .
&quot; sometimes there are long @-@ term survivors , &quot; says Treasure .
but in the end they all die .
fortunately , some patients actually live long , much longer than expected .
the author Stephen Jay Gould died 20 years after diagnosis .
two and a half years after his own diagnosis , Graham Abbott is still struggling .
after contacting Mesotheliom , Abbott came into contact with Andrew Lawson , who , four years after his diagnosis , had become a one @-@ man support and advisory office for people affected .
&quot; hello , Cancer Center , &quot; he happily presented himself at calls .
&quot; he was very positive , &quot; says Abbott .
he had received his diagnosis 4 years earlier and was still very active .
originally , Abbott had been offered six chemotherapy cycles , which would last four months and would likely extend his life by only one month .
&quot; I was desperate , &quot; he says .
I wanted to give up .
but Lawson managed to &quot; make things appear in a somewhat more positive light . &quot;
after consulting several doctors , Abbott decided to continue his treatment with Prof. Loic Lang @-@ Lazdunski , cardio @-@ thorax specialist at Guy &apos;s .
&quot; we had an advantage by not having to be referred back , I simply called and got an appointment , &quot; Graham admitted .
a normal patient would have to receive a transfer and wait for authorisation of treatment .
money is crucial for Mesotheliom sufferers to see the best available therapies .
but when these treatments inevitably fail , many people are concerned by another financial concern - the future of the families they leave .
and so they turn to the courts in the hope of compensation .
Andrew Lawson contacted Andrew Morgan of Field Fisher Waterhouse LLP .
&quot; it has been known since 1898 that asbestos is extremely dangerous to health , &quot; says Morgan .
but what changed in the 1960 &quot; s was that it was recognized that a very low burden was also a health risk .
and here the negligence of companies began to play a role .
Andrew Lawson and Guy &apos;s Hospital eventually contributed their case , but it was not what Morgan calls &quot; full compensation , &quot; because Lawson could not prove with absolute certainty that his Mesotheliom was due to asbestos contact at Guy &apos;s .
however , after the investigation into his death , a Guy &apos;s spokesman confirmed that &quot; asbestos fibres were removed in the affected cellar area in the 1990s . &quot;
that was too late for Andrew Lawson .
how to remove asbestos
indeed , for Mesotheliom sufferers who seek compensation , it is a huge problem to assign fatal asbestos contact to a company or a job - usually decades after the incidents .
many of their former employers have been sold or closed .
insurance documents can be lost .
and those who oppose claims know that the time is for them , but certainly not with the applicants .
in response to this , there were clear new legislation this year , making it easier for Mesotheliom stakeholders to claim compensation , even if their former employers are no longer found .
the law has established a £ 350 million fund supported by the insurance industry for all those diagnosed after July 2012 , but cannot sue anyone .
in these cases , the plaintiffs receive 80 % of what a court could have given them in a normal compensation process - about £ 120,000 .
some 300 successful applications are expected each year .
like so many Mesotheliom stakeholders , Andrew Morgan thinks that £ 350 million was a &quot; very good job &quot; for the insurance industry .
&quot; this is a deal of insurers for insurers , &quot; he says , and suggests that this sum is a quarter of what insurers should have paid if time had not gone by and Mesotheliom sufferers could find companies and sue them normally .
Mike Penning , then Minister of Labour and Pensioners , also admitted that the law was &quot; not perfect . &quot;
but both Penning and Morgan admitted that rapid action is needed every day , with seven deaths .
&quot; people suffer so much and need help today , &quot; said Penning during the second hearing of the Mesotheliom Act in December last year .
at this time Graham Abbott has been in the hands of Prof. Loic Lang @-@ Lazdunski for 19 months .
after her first consultations , Lang @-@ Lazdunski recommended an operation that he expected a positive effect , unlike Tom Treasure .
this was accompanied by radiation therapy and chemotherapy - a three @-@ way therapy that allows Lang @-@ Lazdunski to present a survival rate of up to 40 % over five years .
Abbott felt strengthened .
&quot; this is , of course , the most important thing , &quot; says Abbott .
this is always seen in patients .
there is something that lets you continue .
when you give in , you get worse .
Graham Abbott underwent the operation in March 2012 .
at the end of August he had the last of the six chemotherapy cycles behind him .
after @-@ care scans showed no signs of disease .
then I had a scan in March 2014 .
there were several cancer spots around my breast .
I have just been 50 .
this is not life @-@ threatening .
that is life @-@ saving .
again Abbott underwent six chemotherapy cycles .
now no trace of tumors is visible anymore .
but the process is physically and psychologically very demanding .
you have to think about practical things - about the money , if I am no longer , for example , or my wife , how the boom time is working .
if you receive bad news , you will be negative .
they must look forward .
as father of Ellie , 16 , and Tamsin , 14 , this is not always easy .
&quot; this is difficult for parents , &quot; he says .
it is difficult to know what to say and how much .
when I received my first diagnosis , I told my girl that I had a disease with which I would not be old .
they reacted very differently .
Tamsin is very healthy and undisturbed .
she told her friends and we soon received a lot of calls .
Ellie was more restrained .
she did not say much .
such talks are something that all cancer patients must pass through .
but for Mesothelian patients , such talks are not permeated by hope , not by a trail of hope for survival .
the disease ( like Stephen Jay Gould in the end ) provides a grim safety .
as Andrew Morgan says , &quot; Mesotheliom is not life @-@ threatening .
