asbestos fibres used for strengthening cooking pots and for greater heat resistance .
Plinius der Ältere describes asbestos .
a tissue has been developed that is not flammable .
I saw napkins from this at parties in the fireplaces .
the use of modern commercial asbestos begins in Italy , where it is used to produce paper ( including notes ) and fabric .
important asbestos mines are opened in Canada and South Africa and shortly afterwards in America , Italy and Russia .
it is the ideal insulation material for steam engines and turbines of the industrial revolution .
global asbestos production is rising to more than 30,000 tonnes per year .
Prudential statisticians identify an early death rate for those who work with asbestos , and no longer receive life insurance .
Nellie Kershaw dies in Rochdale .
Dr. William Cooke says that asbestos particles in the lungs are &quot; without any reasonable doubt the main cause of death . &quot;
this is the first such case .
Kershaw &apos;s employer , Turner Bros asbestos , accepts no liability .
no compensation is paid .
during World War II , ships were built intensively , one of the most deadly lines with asbestos contact .
voluntary abandonment of the industry to import blue asbestos
a court of appeal confirms the first successful compensation for personal injury in the United Kingdom for contact with asbestos .
global asbestos production is rising to more than 4,213,000 tonnes per year .
Britain imports 139,000 tonnes .
a UK health and safety executive obliges all companies working with asbestos to acquire licences .
the import and use of blue and brown asbestos is prohibited by law in the UK .
any use of asbestos is prohibited in the UK .
the Mesotheliom Act is adopted in the UK .
a £ 350 million compensation programme is announced .
asbestos is banned in more than 50 countries , but white asbestos is still used as cheap building material in many countries of the world .
worldwide production is about 2 million tonnes per year .
China refuses Hong Kong right to vote , protesters swear retaliation
on Sunday , despite increased calls for democratic reforms , the Chinese parliament decided against the nomination of candidates for the 2017 election by Hong Kong electorate .
this approach is likely to fuel Hong Kong &apos;s long @-@ awaited protests , while activists set in motion planning and mobilization within a few hours of the announcement .
the Chinese People &apos;s Congress &apos;s decision basically allows Communist leaders to reject all non @-@ compliant candidates .
&quot; this is not unexpected , but it makes us angry , &quot; said legal expert Emily Lau , Chairman of the Democratic Party .
that is not what Beijing promised .
the people of Hong Kong were attracted .
and it is clear that we are dealing with an authoritarian regime .
in his defense of China &apos;s decision , Li Fei , Deputy Secretary General of the Permanent Committee of the National People &apos;s Congress , said that the admission of public nominations to Hong Kong &apos;s government would be too &quot; chaotic . &quot;
since 1997 , when Britain gave back control of Hong Kong to the Chinese , Beijing has promised to have its residents elected to the government &apos;s head office from 2017 .
the Chinese leadership presented Sunday &apos;s decision as a democratic breakthrough , because Hong Kong &apos;s citizens have a direct right to vote , but the decision also shows that China &apos;s leaders are firmly in control of the process through a Beijing @-@ controlled Nomination Committee .
under a new clause , only candidates will be admitted &quot; with love for the country and love for Hong Kong . &quot;
the decision follows a summer in which some of the largest and most popular protests in Hong Kong have been taking place for many years .
behind the pro @-@ democratic campaign in Hong Kong is the Occupy Central With Love and Peace movement , whose organizers threatened to shut off the financial district if Beijing does not allow a genuine universal right to vote .
on Sunday evening , hundreds of Occupy Central supporters had gathered in rain in front of Hong Kong &apos;s government headquarters within hours of the announcement .
during the demonstration , the organizers said that their movement had reached a new stage of civilian disobedience and planned protest waves in the coming weeks .
however , they did not provide any further information to avoid problems with the authorities .
in an online communication , the organisers indicated that &quot; the movement considered the occupation of the central district only as a last resort , an action that should only take place when all the possibilities for dialogue have been exhausted and there is no other choice .
we are sorry to say that all the opportunities for dialogue have been exhausted today and that the occupation of the central district will definitely take place .
the Hong Kong authorities have been preparing for Beijing &apos;s announcement for days , and on Sunday strengthened security measures , including police forces and barricades , were taking place in front of the government building .
the unrest is reinforced by the feeling of many in Hong Kong that they are slowly losing control of their city .
the influx of people from the mainland increases competition for products and services .
there is also a growing fear that Hong Kong &apos;s values , such as democracy and freedom of speech , will begin to crumble under growing pressure from Beijing .
some criticized the Occupy Central Movement demonstrations as they jeopardize Hong Kong &apos;s business operations - the lifeline .
&quot; the protests they are talking about could cause major economic damage , depending on how many people are involved and how long they last , &quot; said Lazio Ip , a legal expert who has long criticised the movement .
we do not want to fuel fears that Hong Kong will be out of control .
this impression is bad for investment .
China &apos;s state @-@ controlled media recently reported on democracy activists in Hong Kong as subversive agents controlled by Western powers .
this summer , activists organized an unofficial referendum on electoral rights , in which 780,000 people participated - more than one @-@ fifth of Hong Kong voters .
in July , tens of thousands took part in one of the largest democratic demonstrations in the history of the region .
