feminists criticise racial and police behaviour in Ferguson
the unarmed teenager was killed earlier this month by a police officer in Ferguson , Mo.
the participants raised their hands into the air and sang , &quot; hands high , not shoot , &quot; while waiting for the funeral .
after two weeks of protests in Ferguson , Mo , because of the shooting of the unarmed teenager Michael Brown , the blogger Miriam Zoila Perez noticed a change in the online discussions of white feminists .
according to their experience , white feminist commentators put gender before race when it comes to addressing reproductive law and income inequality .
but , while tensions in the Middle West increased and received attention throughout the country , Perez saw that white women &apos;s responses turned 100 % around the race .
compared to the answers of black women shortly after the shots of 9 August , personal essays with titles such as &quot; thoughts to Ferguson from a white woman &quot; and &quot; feminism is not just about suppressing women &quot; relatively late .
but for Perez , that meant an important change .
&quot; I do not believe that feminism has many people who are talking about white and privileges in such a high @-@ class way , &quot; she said .
people felt urged to express something about what happened .
it is characteristic of the crisis in which we find ourselves and because the situation in Ferguson is so ethnical that they must express it .
for English professor Koritha Mitchell of Ohio State University , Ferguson brought to light problems faced every day by black American women who are not considered &quot; women &apos;s issues &quot; in the cultural sphere .
&quot; I can publish something fun on Facebook about me and my partner and get 150 bikes from anywhere , &quot; Mitchell said .
when I talk about how farmers are under siege in their own country , silence is depressing .
&quot; how can it be safe for women to talk publicly about a relationship , but not about public security ? &quot; she asked .
for black women like Mitchell , who have studied race , gender , and sexuality in US history , there is no dichotomy between racial and gender problems .
for them , black women have not had the luxury of cleaning up the issues ; they live every day in the combined reality .
while white women now combine race and gender in feminist mainstream circles , Angela Hattery , professor of women and gender research at George Mason University , says that their predecessors did the opposite .
&quot; between 1865 and 1890 , at least 10,000 black men were sampled and the justification was almost always the rape of a white woman , &quot; Hattery said .
white women had to be involved in history to justify Lynch &apos;s murder .
for Hattery , the split between white and black women came at the point where white clamps for women &apos;s voting rights , such as Susan B. Anthony , analyzed the country in the late nineteenth century and found that the struggle for electoral rights could only be successful for one group : women or black .
&quot; they took the decision to defend women &apos;s electoral rights , and the right to vote for black should come later , &quot; Hattery said .
if you remember such things , you will know with power why coloured women do not trust white women .
we did not do our job well .
we have never helped black women protect their husbands and sons .
even after women were given the right to vote in 1920 , it took a decade for white women to organize themselves against Lynch in the Association of Southern Woman for the Prevention of Lynching .
the group was formed almost 40 years after the original request for help from black women , says Mitchell .
for Mitchell , the flood of white feminist reactions to the questions raised by Ferguson - police behavior , racial discrimination - is a mirror of the time when white feminists played &quot; catch &quot; with the problems that black women have been dealing with for generations .
&quot; would it not be great for the activists who have such traditional feminist platforms to have the right to educate a child as seriously as they do with the right to contraception ? &quot;
second generation feminists who built up their careers in the struggle for reproductive rights and access to contraceptive means are now trying to understand what that means .
the well @-@ known white feminist activist Gloria Steiner went two weeks after Michael Brown &apos;s shooting on Facebook and published a pointed article by Rebecca Carroll , Guardian &apos;s columnist calling for more protests from white Americans on racism .
&quot; I hope that women who have another but parallel reason to understand a danger inherent in the body - and opinions about the race , which are clearly different in public polls - will lead the changes , &quot;
although Steiner stands for more intersectional feminism , which addresses racial and gender issues , some of her comments on racial issues in America are puzzled .
Christina Sommers , researcher at the American Enterprise Institute and author of &quot; Who stole Feminism ? &quot; said to She The People that young men in the United States , especially young coloured men , are &quot; far more vulnerable than their sisters , &quot; but Steinem &apos;s remarks about Ferguson are contrary to their earlier criticisms .
there are now hundreds of special programs for girls and young women , but almost nothing for boys .
but when the White House recently set up a small program , My Brother &apos;s Keeper , to help vulnerable young black and hispanic men , there were annoying reactions from many feminists , including Gloria Steiner .
the relationship between the police and the black community is not the only problem that comes to the fore of mainstream feminism .
after the US border police picked up almost 63,000 unaccompanied minors at the country &apos;s south @-@ west border this year , the issue of immigration reform is returning to the surface - this time as a women &apos;s issue .
Andrea Mercado , Co @-@ Chair of We Belong Together , an organization that mobilizes women for immigration reform , said that for the issue to be considered as an essential women &apos;s issue , she only had to publish the stories of immigrant women .
&quot; these speak for themselves , &quot; Mercado said .
when the vast majority of work visas go to male immigrants , the women they accompany are in a position where they are vulnerable to domestic violence and exploitation .
&quot; these stories are reflected in women &apos;s organisations , &quot; she said .
