Ebola : the epidemic is affecting West Africa &apos;s economy
the Ebola epidemic in West Africa is also a serious blow to the economy .
markets are orphaned - and international companies are at a distance .
the devastating Ebola epidemic is a serious blow to West Africa &apos;s economy .
the harvest rotates in the fields , the mines are left and the markets are washed - the virus has made the region difficult to grow .
some international companies are already at a distance .
&quot; the Ebola epidemic is not only a medical crisis , but also an economic one , &quot; says the head of the African Development Bank , Donald Kaberuka .
Liberia is hardest hit
&quot; it is a total disaster , we lose a lot of money , &quot; says Alhaji Bamogo , who sells clothes on the second largest market in Liberian capital Monrovia .
only those who want to buy food or something to disinfect Ebola will be on the market .
Liberia has been hit hardest by the virus , with over 600 victims alone .
recently , the health authorities declared that the disease had penetrated every corner of the country .
the virus has also spread in Guinea , Sierra Leone and Nigeria .
in total , more than 1500 people have died and thousands more have died .
foreign companies withdraw employees
companies are starting to operate everywhere in resource @-@ rich countries .
foreign companies such as the Arcelor Mittal steel group withdraw their employees and several international airlines no longer fly to the affected regions .
local traders and farmers are also reacting : few merchants are still leaving their homes to get supplies .
in some areas of Sierra Leone and Liberia , which are quarantine , among other things , the cocoa and coffee beans that are important for export are being destroyed in the fields .
farmers do not dare to leave their homes for the harvest .
food is scarce
&quot; people will travel less and less , &quot; says Phillipe De Vreyer , Paris expert on West Africa &apos;s economy .
the man who normally goes to the market and sells his vegetables , for example , remains at home .
the population is therefore feeling the consequences of the epidemic directly and urgently : food is scarce .
in the markets , stocks of basic foodstuffs such as rice disappear .
at the same time , the region heavily dependent on international companies is threatened with an image - with far @-@ reaching consequences .
the greatest danger is that international companies will avoid the area for a long time , says Philippe Hugon of French Think Tank Iris .
what is crucial is how far and how long the virus will spread .
investors may have the impression that &quot; it is dangerous to live in Guinea , Sierra Leone , and Liberia and thus to invest , &quot; Hugon warns .
the disease also affects the Member States &apos; strained national budgets
the disease also affects the already tight national budgets of the countries concerned .
the rating agency Moody &apos;s fears that its budgets will be heavily strained by the high spending on the health system and , in addition , by the deteriorating economy .
the African Development Bank has already promised to provide $ 60 million ( € 45 million ) to the health systems of the affected countries .
the impact is already felt in Nigeria , where so far only a few Ebola cases have been diagnosed .
although the oil @-@ rich region of southern Nigerdelta has not yet been affected .
but elsewhere , many people remain at home for fear of contagion .
reservations in hotels also go down significantly .
protect your 50th anniversary
the Schützenverein &quot; Tannenwald &quot; Berngau celebrates its 50th anniversary from 12 to 14 September .
at the Schützenverein Tannenwald , preparations for the 50 @-@ year @-@ old foundation festival are under way .
on Friday , September 12 , a great entertainment evening with the group &quot; Dorfrocker . &quot;
on Saturday , at 6 p.m. , the big archery shooting will take place .
then there is the &quot; Stoapfalzer Spitzbuam . &quot;
brass band provides music
highlights on Sunday are the festive service and 9.30 am in the parish church and the large fortress at 2.00 pm .
in the afternoon there is also the distribution of the price of the federal and palate .
a particularly beautiful sight will be the 25 festive dams with their Dirndln .
the festival chapel is Berngau .
the patronage was taken over by Mayor Wolfgang Wild and State Secretary Albert Füracker .
the original name &quot; Schützengesellschaft Tannenwald Berngau &quot; dates back to 1907 , when the association was founded on March 21 for &quot; social entertainment through exercise in the shooting of rooms and small California . &quot;
the NS regime in 1937 led to the dissolution of the association .
only in 1964 did 19 young men find themselves again , who , on 30 April , raised the &quot; new &quot; Schützenverein &quot; Tannenwald &quot; Berngau from the baptism .
Karl March and Adolf Ried led the club as a protector through a difficult initial period , focusing on finding a club location and installing shooting .
as early as autumn 1965 , the Schützenverein in the &quot; Leininger &quot; inn started with two teams in the race .
in the following years , the sports clubs , which were now organized in seven teams , established themselves in all classes up to the 1st Gauliga .
each year the association records were purged and the magic limit of 380 rings was reached for the first time in 1980 by Rudi Meier .
just as the efficiency of active protection has increased , the number of members has also improved .
after the &quot; Leininger &quot; association ceased to meet the demands of a modern protective association , the then board , led by Johann Rinn , decided to create a future domicile in the cellars of the new &quot; Landgasthof Härteis . &quot;
after an employment of 2700 hours on 8 May 1988 , Parish Strasser awarded the church blessing for the new protected areas .
one of the great highlights of the association &apos;s history was certainly the 44th Gaushoot , combined with the festive course of the new protective flag in July 1991 .
on 23 and 24 April 1994 the Schützenverein celebrated its 30th anniversary .
a Böllergruppe was founded in 1995 .
Josef Schmalzl became Böllerreferent .
a major challenge for the &quot; Böllerer &quot; and for the club as a whole was the orientation of the Bavarian Böllertreffen 2005 .
in many hours of volunteer work , the members of the association last year modernized the rooms and sliding facilities in the Berngau Hof , bringing them up to date with the latest technology .
eleven teams in round competitions
you can also see the sporting achievements of the protective association .
in total , eleven teams are currently taking part in the race competitions : six air competition teams , an air pistols team , a sports pistols K1 , a youth team and two AH teams .
the first team with Lars Ellrich , Katharina Ellrich , Steffi Grad and Kerstin Kellermann went up to the District League 1 in the 2013 / 14 round .
the second team with Verena Moosburger Alexandra Meier , Eva Schuhmann and Tobias Graml went from Gauliga Nord to Gauoberliga .
in addition to shooting sports , events such as bowling , carnival and royal ball , club excursion and Christmas tradition are also held .
with them , they are also at the festivals in parish and community .
