tax burden on businessmen in the Washington area increases with economic recovery
economic recovery means more customers , more sales and new jobs .
it also means higher taxes .
government and local tax rulings for companies in the country increased slightly last year , while economic recovery accelerated , according to a newly published study last week , and firms in Washington were no exception .
companies in District , Maryland , and Virginia jointly paid $ 27.6 billion to government and local authorities in 2013 , an increase of 3.8 % compared to 2012 revenues of $ 26.6 billion .
companies &quot; government and local tax burden increased by 4.3 % last year to $ 671 billion , compared to 3.9 % a year earlier , and it was the third consecutive year of growth after several years of declining 2009 and 2010 .
government taxes rose by 4.3 % more than local taxes , according to the study carried out by the Service Agency Ernst &amp; Young with the Centre for State Taxation , a tax policy group .
more than half of the district &apos;s tax revenues , 56 % , come from corporate taxes , while 36 % of Maryland &apos;s revenues come from companies .
Virginia generates the lowest tax revenue from companies at 28 % .
much of the increase in tax revenues is due to a recovery in corporate real estate assets , researchers say , leading to an increase in real estate taxes of 3.7 % this year after the three consecutive years , with growth rates of less than 1 % .
while much of these profits came from large states such as California , New York , and Texas , the course of events seems to be true for the Washington area .
companies in the District , Maryland , and Virginia jointly paid more than $ 10 billion in government and local real estate taxes last year , compared to $ 9.6 billion in 2012 - an increase of 4.2 % over a year .
but the apparent recovery in real estate values in Maryland is not so effective in increasing government and local tax revenues , as real estate taxes account for just over one @-@ fifth of companies &quot; tax rulings .
companies in Virginia and D.C. pay almost half of their state and local taxes in the form of real estate taxes .
&quot; in Maryland , a large part of the real estate , especially in the tax area around D.C. , is owned either by the government or by non @-@ profit organizations that do not pay real estate taxes , &quot; said Douglas Lindholm , Center on State Taxation .
for example , Maryland is forced to rely much more on income taxes to provide the same services that other states offer .
the recent recovery in corporate tax revenues cannot be attributed solely to the recovery of the real estate market
corporate income also appears to be recovering , according to data .
companies in the region reported income taxes on state organizations of $ 2.3 billion compared to 2.1 billion in 2012 .
Maryland included $ 1 billion in corporate income taxes , the region &apos;s highest amount .
while the trend is in the same direction , the local tax burden on businesses is not increasing evenly in all three places .
the district growth rate was 4.3 % in line with the national average , while the rise in Maryland was significantly higher , 4.9 % .
only Virginia reported below @-@ average tax revenue of 4.1 % .
Virginia has the lowest company income tax in all three areas of office ( all three have fixed corporate tax rates ) .
the corporate tax rate in Maryland is 8.25 % and the district at a relatively high 9.975 % .
a comparable study by the US Chamber of Commerce at the beginning of this year showed that in Virginia , less government and local corporate taxes are required and that overall there is a better tax climate than in Maryland .
the study did not examine the district .
despite the benefits , Virginia is under pressure from its southern neighbour .
North Carolina has passed laws to reduce its corporate tax rates from 6.9 % this year to 6 % , the same rate as Virginia , and the rate will fall to 5 % next year .
if the government continues to meet its income targets next year , this law could reduce the government &apos;s corporate income tax rate to 3 % by 2017 .
meanwhile , small businesses in the Washington area seem to be doing better , so they pay more government and local taxes , according to the latest study .
corporate taxes paid as personal income taxes by small businessmen - a transitional structure for which most small businesses are organized - in the district , Maryland , and Virginia rose by 20 % last year to $ 2.4 billion , a much faster rate of growth than corporate taxes as a whole .
researchers say that the trend and increase in corporate taxes throughout the country is likely to continue this year , with a 6.2 % increase in the general tax revenue for government and local governments over the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period of the previous year .
yet Washington could lag behind if the federal government &apos;s spending cut had an impact on the labor market in the region .
