Amazon buys Twitch for $ 1.04 billion
Amazon just confirmed what information had reported on Monday morning : the online retailer - and video producer , and a variety of other things - buys the video streamlining service Twitch for $ 1.04 billion ( $ 970 million ) .
the announcement comes as a surprise , not because nobody expected Twitch to take over , but because it was widely believed that YouTube would acquire the company .
three months ago , it looked as though the sale of Twitch to Google &apos;s video service was decided for a cool billion , and the cooperation seemed natural .
twitch , founded only three years ago as Justin.tv , was launched as a general streaming service - a live version of YouTube .
instead , it quickly became a platform for players who wanted to publish their Bravo pieces in games , a &quot; YouTube for live games , &quot; so an insider .
the Twitch interface .
and &quot; let &apos;s play , &quot; a video genre in which better known ( mostly older ) games give a touch of secrecy theatre , is already very popular on YouTube .
it &apos;s the case that YouTube is often called when you want to describe Twitch , so the message that YouTube wanted to buy Twitch was taken up a bit , a textbook example of a well @-@ established technology company buying up a potential competitor .
it is a mystery why the deal with YouTube did not come about , because the company was reported to be willing to pay as much as Amazon .
all we know at the moment is this statement by Emmet Shear , President of Twitch : &quot; we have chosen Amazon because they believe in our community , they share our values and long @-@ term visions and they want to help us get there faster . &quot;
another secret is , frankly , the incredible success of Twitch .
for Snobs like myself , who explain that they prefer to practice sport rather than watch it , it is hard to understand the attraction that comes from watching others play instead of taking the control panel in hand .
it is one thing to look over the shoulder of a friend at 3 o &apos;clock in the morning , while Resident Evil is shining , and something quite different to watch a spinner watch him shot into the head 20 times in Call of Duty .
all these games could be seen right now .
another problem is that many of the most popular games today are ego games , so watching without your own control over the perspective can be a good recipe for headache .
I admit that the rapid rounds in which the Roger Bannisters of our electronic age are playing in record time are entertaining .
but until a game or humor virtuoso is present , his Twitch channel is probably not so interesting .
but what do skeptics like me know ?
twitch is called by 55 million different visitors per month and is the fourth largest source of Internet traffic peaks .
and how exactly does Amazon want to make money ?
it &apos;s hard to imagine that Twitch is so elegantly integrated into Amazon Instant Video as YouTube Twitch could easily have swallowed .
but Twitch has something every company would like : thousands of young men who are recruited as advertisers .
as the chairman of Twitch , Shear , said Amazon and Twitch &quot; both believe in the future of gaming , &quot; and the medium does not show signs of shrinkage , not even - shame - as a spectator sport .
